To begin with, there was no &quot;Schlieffen Plan&quot;,
only a &quot;Schlieffen Proposal&quot;. Schlieffen never
worked out the details of it.

Second, the Schlieffen Proposal called for a
much larger army than Germany actually had in
1914.

Third, Schlieffen called for the German march
to pass through the Netherlands as well as
Belgium. This would have guaranteed British
intervention.

Fourth, the invasion of the Netherlands
might not have gone well. The Dutch army
mobilized in 1914, a few days before
Germany. Apparently part of the telegraph
system in western Germany was operated by
a company with mixed German and Dutch
ownership. The Dutch owners cooperated
with the Dutch intelligence service and
placed agents at the main exchange in
Germany; these agents saw messages clearly
indicating that Germany was going to war,
and alerted the Dutch government.

Fifth, to assemble the required forces
in the west, Schlieffen's proposal
stripped the east of all but a skeleton
defense force. There could be no
Tannenberg. The German offensive in
France has to win completely, and
quickly, because by the end of August
the Russians will have Konigsberg and
Danzig under siege, and be moving
toward the Oder with little to stop
them.
