The problem is the eternal bugbear of logistics and mobility. The
Germans were physically unable to move much beyond the Marne even if
they had won a crashing victory there. Although feeding the troops was
doable (by a combination of living off the land and iron rations) the
German horses - both cavalry mounts and draught animals - were in a
sorry state even by the Marne, which crippled the cavalry and prevented
the movement of artillery: Moltke himself described the Army as lacking
a single horse able to drag itself forwards. Ammunition was even worse,
with the supply columns lagging far behind the troops and desperate
expedients of commandeered motor-cars being required to get rounds
forward to the fighting: sixty per cent of what motor transport the
Germans had, had broken down by the Marne.

