I don't quite follow.

The Germans managed to _retreat_ all the way to the Aisne - about 50 miles
in places. Presumably if they and their horses could go that distance
northward they could (had the battle gone differently) have gone a
comparable distance south.

Had they done so, the _French_ would have started having logistical
problems, since the Germans would have been across the railway lines between
the capital and the eastern frontier of France - through which the French
armies in Lorraine were getting their supplies. And if those have to fall
back, the _German_ supply situation is much eased, as supplies can be sent
direct rather than via Belgium.

I quite agree the Germans won't get an instant KO, 1940-style. Things are
too &quot;slow motion&quot; for that, and there's plenty of space into which the
French can retreat. But I suspect they win in the end. It all sounds a lot
like 1870, with most of northern France in German hands and the French
hanging on as best they can in the Provinces. And if the Paris region goes,
most of France's remaining industry goes with it, so while the French may
hang on well into 1915, I find it hard to see how they win the war from that
position.
--

