But _IF_ it gets to this point, situation becames really interesting:
France is out and this leaves Russia more or less alone against
Germany and A-H. On one hand, Russia is reasonably successful against
both: it occupies a big part of the Eastern Prussia and Galitsia
(IIRC, Brusilov took Lwowv by the time of OTL Tannenberg). OTOH, it
CAN NOT continue war with any chance for success because Germany alone
is quite obviously (I think that this was obvious even to Nicholas)
stronger military and economically.

Which brings a number of possibilities:

1. A speedy peace between Russia and Germany/A-H, probably along pre-
war borders, as soon as France gets out of war (and before Germany
reallocates necessary forces to the East).

2. Nicholas decides to fight alone (Brittish help on land can be
discounted). A _fast_ defeat of Russia. Depending on how fast this
defeat happens and the conditions of peace, it may or may not mean
revolution and overthrow of a monarchy. If defeat happens fast enough
and the peace conditions are relatively generous, than monarchy can
survive:
a. the war did not yet become a national disaster in the terms of
losses and economical hardships.
b. the earlier sucesses would allow at least some face saving and the
blame can be put on the allies.
