You sure?

My old _Muir's Historical Atlas_ shows a rail line running
Metz-Conflans-Verdun-Chalons-Epernay-Chateau-Thierry-Meaux-Paris, most of
which was in German hands in early Sep 1914. Banks' _Military Atlas of the
First World War_ also shows a line running through Metz and Verdun, while
Corelli Barnett's _The Swordbearers_ includes a railway map of France which,
though annoyingly small scale, shows what appears to be the same line.

Obviously it wouldn't be much use as long as the French clung on to Verdun,
but at the time of the FBotM Verdun is already up at the end of a precarious
salient, and it's a bit difficult to see it holding if the Germans advance
any further.

I agree that German supplies were, so far, having to come through Belgium,
but was that purely a railway matter? As long as the French were holding on
from Verdun to Belfort, there were very few routes from Germany to France
_except_ via Belgium, either by rail or any other way. But it looks to me as
if that would become less true if the French had to retire any further.

[snip]

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Trouble is, how do you take Paris with no artillery?
">

You probably can't, immediately. But that is not essential. Your principal
objective is not Paris, but the French Army.

The real importance of Paris, apart from its sentimental value for the
French (it is, well - - - Paris) and prestige value for the Germans, is as a
railway junction - indeed _the_ main nexus of the rail lines of all Northern
France - in particular iro the railway lines supplying the French armies in
the east. If the Germans can sever those lines, taking the city itself would
be helpful, but in the short term at least, not vital.

Indeed, even if the Germans _did_ come to a standstill shortly after winning
the FBotM, if that left a Western Front running through the suburbs of Paris
it ought
to be possible for the Germns to cripple the French by making those rail
junctions unusable.

