Lots of arguments here, and e.g. in US Civil War discussions,
based on the possession and use of railroads.  Which leads me
to the question, how fast could a determined nation with lots of
military and other laborers to call on _build_ a railroad where it
was needed, on a crash program basis?  Land acquisition is
a nonissue, you blow away anybody who argues.  Bridges would
perhaps be the biggest problem -- in WWI, could something
like a pontoon bridge be built that would stand the weight of a
locomotive (freight cars are duck soup after that)?  At this stage,
there was no such thing as behind the lines air attack, railroad
builders would be undisturbed except by the weather and delays
in supplies.  Such few tunnels as you would need via Belgium
and Northwest France could largely be replaced by massive
and unattractive blasting away of hillsides.  No civilian traffic to
consider, no stations except  for handling troops and materiel.
