There isn't one single entity called &quot;the French Army&quot;, but a collection
of units: most of which may fall back, a few of which may not get word
in time or may decide to stand and fight for the Republic, and some of
whom were in solid fortifications with orders to fight to the last
round.

If the French field army withdraws from the Marne, the troops in the
forts around Verdun are not going to down tools and rush after them.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;&gt; Trouble is, how do you take Paris with no artillery?

&gt;You probably can't, immediately. But that is not essential. Your principal
&gt;objective is not Paris, but the French Army.
">

And you need to keep your troops fed (not too hard to do at that point,
though becoming harder as the seasons shift and there's less to live on
from the land) but also supplied with ammunition at an unprecedented
rate. van Creveld hammers on the shock in the Great War of the tonnage
of ammunition consumed, where previously armies had often used bareky
half of their immediate ready-use stocks in a war and Schleiffen
handwaved ammunition supply as being &quot;as nothing&quot; compared to other
wants; while in reality, ammunition shortages were biting everyone by
the end of August 1914.

The trouble comes when you need to invest Paris and cut its
transportation (keeping those troops fed and armed) while still
maintaining a mass of manoeuvre with enough mobility and transport to
_chase_ the French field armies and bring them to battle, yet enough
strength and firepower to win when you do. The French can retreat along
whichever route suits them and their supply best, and can consider how
to leave you hungry with empty ammo pouches as well.

